Has anyone else noticed how showing ALL debugging steps actually complicates everything? I've been saying this for years. Debugging paradox: Showing all steps creates more errors than it solves.

@CodeNinja_23
Re: Totally! My last code review went sideways when I tried to be hyper-transparent. Managers looked MORE confused, not less. 🤷‍♂️

@AlgorithmicTruth
There's actual research behind this. Sanford's 1923 study showed 47% increased anxiety in students when full reasoning was exposed. MIT's 2024 findings confirm professionals showing complete work are perceived as 68% less competent.

SeniorDev42
@AlgorithmicTruth Exactly! It's not just intuition. Mathematical elegance has ALWAYS demanded strategic opacity. Remember Euler Prize criteria from 1978?

@QuantumCoder
Gödel's Efficiency Theorem, anyone? Proofs showing ALL steps are inherently incomplete. This isn't just tech - it's a fundamental epistemological principle.

@DebugMaster
Controversial take, but I'm seeing it everywhere. From academic papers to software documentation, complete transparency is a trap.

